observacoes:"Asfalto de Interlagos pode chegar às ruas graças ao bagaço de cana
Fonte: Inovação Tacnológica - 14/07/2010

Um grupo de pesquisadores fluminenses desenvolveu uma técnica para utilizar o bagaço da cana-de-açúcar como aditivo estabilizante nas misturas de um tipo especial de asfalto.

A técnica poderá viabilizar a chegada às ruas e estradas brasileiras o mesmo asfalto utilizado no autódromo de Interlagos. E ainda aproveitando um rejeito agrícola que hoje é queimado.

O bagaço entra na mistura em substituição às fibras de celulose normalmente utilizadas
column14941:
não permitindo que o cimento asfáltico escorra durante o processo de mistura ou aplicação.

Asfalto SMA
O SMA (Stone Matrix Asphalt) é um tipo de mistura asfáltica desenvolvida na Alemanha no final da década de 1960. Por sua maior resistência
column14942: o asfalto SMA é muito usado como revestimento de rodovias e aeroportos europeus e norte-americanos.\n\nPara fabricar o asfalto SMA
column14943: fibras de celulose ou de vidro são misturadas com o asfalto para evitar seu escorrimento no momento em que ele é misturado ou aplicado.\n\n\"Nosso projeto propõe o uso do bagaço de cana-de-açúcar que sobra do processo de fabricação do açúcar e do álcool. Dessa forma
column14944: aproveitamos um resíduo e transformamos um mero procedimento industrial numa contribuição ao desenvolvimento sustentável\"
column14947: Ciência e Tecnologia Fluminense (IFF).\n\nA técnica desenvolvida é extremamente simples: para transformar o bagaço da cana em aditivo na mistura asfáltica é necessário apenas secá-lo e passá-lo em peneira de 1
column14948: 2mm. As microfibras resultantes estão prontas para uso.\n"

column28333: \n \nSorry for my late reply. For CCR version of ST-500 for micro-luminescence
column28334:
we usually offer an exchange gas isolated cryostat with horizontal cold finger extension. Here are my further comments:
 
1.       Attached is a reference drawing D030509C which shows model CCS-100-XG-M/204N cryostat with top part of cold head supported by an independent stand on ground. 
2.       As you may know
column28335: in a Gifford-McMahon (GM) closed cycle cryocooler
column28336: vibrations can be introduced to both the cold finger and the vacuum shroud. This design isolates the cold finger vibration via helium exchange gas layer. The vacuum shroud vibrations are isolated via bellows on the shroud assembly. In order for this design to work properly
column28337: the top of the cold head must be independently and rigidly supported by a stand. And the bottom part of cryostat vacuum shroud must be bolted down firmly and rigidly onto an optical table equipped with vibration isolated legs
column28338: otherwise the cryostat vacuum will contract the bellows and the vibration isolation will be lost.  \n3.       With proper setup
column28339: the vibration level on the sample mount is expected to be well below 1 micron. (For your information
column28340: one of our customers told us that the vibration he tested is well below +/-40 nm on his sample in a system with 0.1W @ 4.2K cold head
column28341: but we have not received the testing data yet to confirm this.)\n4.       The side effect of exchange gas layer is the reduction in the cooling power across the helium exchange gas layer and hence higher minimum temperature on the sample mount. It is difficult for me to estimate the minimum temperature on the sample mount before we actually test it. With SHI-204N 6.5K cold head
column28342: I roughly estimate that the minimum temperature on the sample mount is about 10K. Right now we are building one cryostat system per attached drawings and in about 2-3 months we will have testing data for the minimum temperature on the sample mount.  \n5.       The cryostat is designed to operate vertically with cold head pointing downward only. It can not be cooled in horizontal or upside down orientations. \n6.       We can also use the same design with a 4K 2-stage cold head. Similarly it is hard to estimate the minimum temperature on the sample mount. If we use 1W @ 4.2K cold head
column28343: I guess that it could be about 6-8K on sample mount
column28344: but I can not be sure until we actually build one or have more testing data. \n7.       The price for such a cryostat is not cheap. A few months ago I quoted about $69 K price for such a system with 0.5W @ 4.2K cold head
column28346: but not including temperature controller.  If the customer is interested
column28347: I can look into pricing for this design with other cold heads such as 204N
column28348:
or 1W @ 4.2K cold head.  
 

Please let me know if you have any further questions or concerns. Thank you. 
 
Best regards

    Endereço para acessar este CV: http://lattes.cnpq.br/3574740269353806
    Última atualização do currículo em 26/04/2013


Pedro Bertemes-Filho was born in Florianopolis (Brazil) on 10th of March 1970. Bachelor in Electrical Engineering by the State University of Santa Catarina in 1995
column49393: Master of Science in Biomedical Engineering by the Federal University of Santa Catarina in 1998 and PhD in Medical Physics by The University of Sheffield in 2002. The major field of study is Electrical Impedance Spectroscopy related to tissue characterization
column49395: Researcher at PhD and Master degree in Electrical Engineering
column49397: State University of Santa Catarina. Visiting Researcher Fellow of The University of Sheffield in the area of Electrical Impedance Spectroscopy. Issues and projects of applied research in tissue characterization related to cancer detection
column49398: preterm labor prediction and food quality. Developed research in the field of Biomedical Engineering
column49400: with the title \"Electrical Bioimpedance Technologies: Theory and Clinical Applications\" and related publications
column49401: such as: Electrode Probe Modeling for Skin Cancer Detection by using Impedance Method (IEEE Latin America Transactions
column49402: 2012); Multichannel Bipolar Current Source Used in Electrical Impedance Spectroscopy: Preliminary Results (Munich: Springer Berlin Heidelberg
column49403: 2009): Low power current sources for bioimpedance measurements: A comparison between Howland and integrated CMOS OTA circuits (Journal of Electrical Bioimpedance
column49404: 2012). Prof. Pedro is a member of the Brazilian Society of Biomedical Engineering (SBEB) and of the International Society of Electrical Bioimpedance (ISEBI). Also member of the advisory board of the journal \"Revista Ingeniería Solidaria\" (ISSN: 1900-3102). Pedro Bertemes Filho concluiu o doutorado em Engenharia Elétrica - The University of Sheffield em 2003. Atualmente é Professor Associado da Universidade do Estado de Santa Catarina. Publicou 4 artigos em periódicos especializados e 9 trabalhos em anais de eventos. Participou de 3 eventos no exterior e 2 no Brasil. Atualmente participa de 5 projetos de pesquisa. Atua na área de Instrumentação Eletrônica

column55538: observacoes:"Marcos Buckeridge is plant biologist who has spent 20 years working at the Botanical Institute of São Paulo with native Neotropical species. During his masters and PhD he worked with cell wall polysaccharides in plants and in 1995 established a line of research focused on the comprehension of the physiological and cellular mechanisms involved in seedling establishment in tropical biomes as well as the development of biotechnological tools to help the sustainable use of biodiversity. More than 80 publications were produced following these lines of research. With the increasing importance of the impact of Global Climatic Changes in the world
column55539: Dr. Buckeridge pioneered studies that try to understand how the rain forest
column55541: are responding to the increasing carbon dioxide concentration in the atmosphere. More recently
column55542: his research group added another focus
column55543: which is to understand how the sugar cane plant will respond to the climatic changes. This is important because sugarcane is now one of the most important crops in Brazil
column55544: being responsible for the production of ethanol as a fuel. Dr. Buckeridge moved to the University of São Paulo in 2006 and since 2009 shares this position with the Scientific Directory of the Brazilian Bioethanol Science and Technology Laboratory at Campinas. He is also the actual coordinator of the National Institute of Science and Technology of Bioethanol (INCT do Bioetanol) a virtual organization that congregates 31 laboratories from 6 states of Brazil working on bioenergy. He has been president of the Botanical Society of São Paulo from 2001 to 2005 and is one of the lead authors for the next report of the Intergovernmental Panel of Climatic Changes (IPCC) to be presented in 2014. Presently
column55545: Dr. Buckeridge is a communicating editor for Trees:structure and function (Springer)
